    "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM creates an invisible barrier for underrepresented groups, where fear of conforming to outdated stereotypes can stifle innovation and equity. Addressing it isn’t just about fairness—it’s critical for harnessing diverse perspectives that drive progress. In STEM fields, where technical problems often require creative solutions, the absence of varied viewpoints can limit breakthroughs. Personally, I’ve seen how this dynamic plays out in team settings; when one member feels self-conscious about their identity, the entire group’s confidence and collaboration suffer. Beyond ethics, STEM thrives on curiosity and risk-taking, qualities that stereotypes can squash by making individuals hesitant to contribute their ideas. To combat this, organizations must foster psychological safety, where everyone feels empowered to speak up without fear of judgment. Training programs that highlight role models from diverse backgrounds, along with inclusive hiring practices, can reshape narratives and break cycles of exclusion. For individuals, cultivating resilience through mentorship and self-advocacy becomes key—challenging stereotypes internally while advocating for inclusive environments externally. Ultimately, addressing stereotype threat isn’t just a moral imperative; it’s a strategic one for advancing science and technology in ways that benefit everyone.",
